TeaganAir
If you asked me to describe what it's like to fly a small plane, I'd say it's like riding a motorcycle/ATV/boat hybrid at 4,000 feet.
On the ground, things are always changing. The ground has a certain level of instability, so you'd need a motorcycle/ATV.
Another thing you might not know is that when you're flying on the ground, you actually control the direction with your feet, not the yoke. You use the rudder pedals and brakes instead. It's not a car.
While flying in the air, you'll feel a lot of turbulence and oscillation, similar to being on a boat in the water. Although you can control the plane, sometimes the air currents will make you feel disoriented, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like a sailor adapts to navigation.
One more thing to share.
Flying is physically demanding. Today, my back and legs are aching badly, feeling like I just worked out at the gym.
It's not as simple as cruising around on Sunday in the car. To me as a beginner, it's more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, have a great Saturday. Welcome to the 4,000-foot sky.
Tomorrow I'll be flying again, and we'll be practicing stall and slow flight.
Today's weather isn't too stable, but it's super fun. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed once dropped to 16 miles per hour, while our airspeed was still 65 miles per hour.
Today's weather is clear, with some fog in the high altitude, but the visibility is still great.
